body_raw:
I was reading my GR textbook when I came across the definition of the covariant derivative in coordinate form. Now, to get some experience with it, I decided to play around with it and see if I could construct some definitions from vector calculus with it. Now, for the Laplacian, this works fine, giving $$
abla^{\mu}\partial_{\mu}\phi=g^{\mu
u}(\partial_{
u}\partial_{\mu}\phi-\Gamma^{\lambda}_{
u\mu}\partial_{\lambda}\phi)$$ This expression works perfectly well for the three-dimensional metrics for spherical, cylindrical, etc.. Note that $\Gamma^{\mu}_{
u\sigma}$ are the Christoffel coefficients describing the Levi-Civita connection. Now, when I try to find, say, a generalized expression for the divergence the same way, $$
abla_{\mu}V^{\mu}=\partial_{\mu}V^{\mu}+\Gamma^{\mu}_{\mu\lambda}V^{\lambda}$$ this fails every time, save for on a Cartesian metric. Why does one work and not the other?

